  fiber: 5 g
  sodium: 1490 mg
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all
produce. Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into 1-inch pieces, if necessary. Toss on
a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%teaspoon}, @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Place @garlic{2%cloves} in the center of a small piece of #foil{};
cinch into a packet and place on same sheet. Roast until broccoli is tender and
garlic is softened, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}(halved, peeled, and thinly
sliced). Dice @roma tomato{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add onion
and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Stir in tomato, half the @balsamic vinegar{5%teaspoon} (all the vinegar
for 4), and @sugar{1%teaspoon} (2 tsp for 4 servings). Cook, stirring, until
soft and jammy, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Turn off heat;
remove jam from pan and set aside. Wipe out pan.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, half the
@fry seasoning{1%tablespoon} (all for 4 servings), @salt{1/2%tsp} (1 tsp for 4),
and @pepper{}. Form mixture into two wide, roughly ½-inch-thick rounds (four
rounds for 4). Divide @cheddar cheese{1/2%cube} between centers of each round.
Fold edges of meat around cheddar, shaping and sealing to create cheese-stuffed
patties, each slightly wider than a burger bun.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in pan used for jam over medium-high heat.
Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

While patties cook, halve @brioche buns{2}; toast until golden brown. Once garlic
is done, remove from foil and mash with a #fork{} until smooth.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @sour cream{2%tablespoon},
and mashed garlic. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Spread buns with @ketchup{2%tablespoon} and a thin layer of sauce. Fill with
patties and top with tomato onion jam. Divide burgers and broccoli between
plates. Serve with any remaining sauce on the side for dipping.

> The Juicy Lucy burger is one that takes you by surprise. It looks unassuming
> from the outside, but hidden deep within its stuffed patty is a core of molten
> cheese just waiting to gush out. Get some napkins and the roasted broccoli ready
> for refreshing yourself between bites of cheddar-filled, beefy decadence.